A New Science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to think about the necessity of a new science, which could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists believe that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
With regard to the great challenges, it is considered that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: First, the great unsolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and third, problems whose solution must be based on scientific grounds, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, many people believe that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
Today's models do work.
However, an increasing group of scientists points to phenomena that are not well explained by today's theories.
These problems do occur more and more frequently, but they are also cleverly circumvented because there is no science that would explain these problems.
This lack of science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is somewhat well established.
Physics, at least the part of it with which we ordinary people are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, but it is expected that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
There are also the new social sciences, which deal with people and societies.
In each of these fields – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and largely uncontroversial.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are simply so different.
This means that we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the inclusion of multiple disciplines.
For example, think of the brain.
This complex organ is composed of molecules whose interaction is based on the foundations of physics. The information conveyed is transmitted according to the laws of electricity.
There is also a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information.
When two brains interact, a new level is introduced: here, information exchange occurs through language, symbols, and concepts.
On each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes on each level.
Information is also exchanged between the different levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
In order to address this deficiency, some scientists have attempted to redefine the instruments used to explain phenomena within one level, in order to apply them to another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem remains unsolved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the different levels and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in the world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this shameful lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who gathered in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from different countries and fields and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are also participating in the discussion.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," in which the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and supplemented and transferred to another level.
Others, however, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
They believe that many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and that new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge from scientists who currently have no access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have, like their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries must build similar resources as industrialized countries. This could however stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centers not associated with the major institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a lack of computing capacity everywhere.
The most brilliant and literally world-changing insights in physics over the past decades did not come, as expected, from the renowned innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that has led cognitive scientists to important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") come today from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified, for which explanations must be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be added to this group, in order to then identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, as one might say.

